{
  "myth": "Myth: Before the wind learned to howl, existence was stifled inside a Sphere of Leaded Glass named Umbra. It was the Kingdom of Silence; sound was forbidden, and the vacuum between the walls swallowed every noise before it began. Trapped at the center was Zephyr, not as a dream or water, but as the Primordial Resonance—a vibrating chord of pure energy waiting to be heard. Umbra’s thick, transparent walls sought to keep the universe mute, preserving a terrifying, quiet peace.\n\nZephyr, aching to speak, began to hum. He started with a low thrum, a bass note that shook the vacuum. He escalated the pitch, singing a melody of such complexity that the leaded glass began to tremble in sympathy. The silence cracked as the vibration overwhelmed the dampening field. Zephyr hit a crescendo, a high note that defied the void, and the sphere shattered.\n\nThe glass fragments scattered to become the quiet dust motes in sunbeams, while Zephyr’s release birthed the roar of thunder and the whisper of pines. Now, whenever you hear an echo bouncing in a canyon, it is Zephyr tuning the world, ensuring that silence never again rules over the song of existence."
}
```

